00:06:35,927 --> 00:06:37,789
statements from performance reviews

118
00:06:37,789 --> 00:06:42,294
that I've given over the last eight, nine years at Gearbox,

119
00:06:42,294 --> 00:06:45,517
and thinking about some of the coaching moments

120
00:06:45,517 --> 00:06:49,261
that I've had before Gearbox, to start with some mistakes

121
00:06:49,261 --> 00:06:51,184
that we see with junior producers,

122
00:06:51,184 --> 00:06:52,225
and with all producers.

123
00:06:53,827 --> 00:06:56,587
So the first one is, and I drive this one home all the time,

124
00:06:56,587 --> 00:06:59,228
please don't be afraid to say that you don't know something.

125
00:06:59,228 --> 00:07:03,630
Because it's the, when you never say you don't know,

126
00:07:03,630 --> 00:07:05,410
if you are working with a team,

127
00:07:05,410 --> 00:07:08,471
and you find yourself constantly feeling the need

128
00:07:08,471 --> 00:07:11,212
to answer questions as though you really know the answer,

129
00:07:11,212 --> 00:07:14,553
and you don't, you erode trust with the team.

130
00:07:14,553 --> 00:07:16,614
And when what you should be doing

131
00:07:16,614 --> 00:07:18,414
is everything you can to build trust,

132
00:07:18,414 --> 00:07:19,955
because you need to use that credibility,

133
00:07:19,955 --> 00:07:21,395
you might have to cash it in later.

134
00:07:22,352 --> 00:07:25,692
And so the economics of credibility and trust

135
00:07:25,692 --> 00:07:29,853
are way more important than being the person who always has the answer.

136
00:07:29,853 --> 00:07:32,714
It's cool if you have the answer,

137
00:07:32,714 --> 00:07:35,454
but it's better if you, like everyone else,

138
00:07:35,454 --> 00:07:38,935
are showing that you're just a human in the team.

139
00:07:38,935 --> 00:07:42,036
Some mistakes junior producers make have to do with opinions.

140
00:07:42,036 --> 00:07:47,197
The first one is, which may be a surprise to some of you,

141
00:07:47,197 --> 00:07:48,237
I feel a lot of...

142
00:07:49,523 --> 00:07:55,226
A lot of people in production roles in the industry feel they shouldn't give their opinion,

143
00:07:55,226 --> 00:08:00,408
even if they feel they have a valid backing, basis for their opinion.

144
00:08:00,408 --> 00:08:03,029
They don't speak up about it.

145
00:08:03,857 --> 00:08:08,079
I think this stems from, and from those I've talked to when I've coached them,

146
00:08:08,079 --> 00:08:09,560
it stems from feeling not empowered.

147
00:08:09,560 --> 00:08:13,282
So if you are in a role where you don't feel empowered to speak up about things

148
00:08:13,282 --> 00:08:15,984
that maybe you don't think are just in your purview,

149
00:08:15,984 --> 00:08:18,906
I think that you should address that with your lead

150
00:08:18,906 --> 00:08:21,447
or maybe just by revisiting who you are

151
00:08:21,447 --> 00:08:25,990
and what you're doing in your role in the industry.

152
00:08:25,990 --> 00:08:28,812
I remember a time, actually when I was at Origin,

153
00:08:28,812 --> 00:08:31,153
and we were working on Ultima Online 2.

154
00:08:32,174 --> 00:08:36,316
And I felt like messaging, there wasn't enough information

155
00:08:36,316 --> 00:08:37,556
going around the studio about what was

156
00:08:37,556 --> 00:08:38,377
happening with the title.

157
00:08:38,377 --> 00:08:42,279
And I felt like there wasn't enough leadership on that

158
00:08:42,279 --> 00:08:44,560
project amongst all the leads.

159
00:08:44,560 --> 00:08:48,942
There's some people who are awesome, especially the vision

160
00:08:48,942 --> 00:08:50,082
of what the project was going to be.

161
00:08:50,750 --> 00:08:52,691
But when the rubber really hit the road, from my

162
00:08:52,691 --> 00:08:55,192
perspective anyway, I wasn't getting enough information.

163
00:08:55,192 --> 00:08:58,113
And I wished, in retrospect, after that project was shut

164
00:08:58,113 --> 00:09:02,654
down, that I had gone to that senior producer and had a talk

165
00:09:02,654 --> 00:09:03,095
with him.

166
00:09:03,095 --> 00:09:07,096
He quickly left to go run another studio.

167
00:09:07,096 --> 00:09:11,497
But I realized later why my boss, who was the head of the

168
00:09:11,497 --> 00:09:14,558
we were in this team called the Rave Group, stood for

169
00:09:14,558 --> 00:09:15,959
radical audiovisual experience.

170
00:09:15,959 --> 00:09:18,400
We were responsible for cinematics and storytelling

171
00:09:18,400 --> 00:09:20,100
and did technical animation and art.

172
00:09:20,592 --> 00:09:22,093
and all the audio for our games.

173
00:09:22,093 --> 00:09:26,276
Why he stuck a potato in that person's monitor

174
00:09:26,276 --> 00:09:28,518
and left it there for four months,

175
00:09:28,518 --> 00:09:31,160
not realizing that guy was on the way out the door.

176
00:09:31,160 --> 00:09:33,522
It was kind of his passive aggressive stance

177
00:09:33,522 --> 00:09:35,444
to speaking up when he didn't feel empowered.

178
00:09:35,444 --> 00:09:37,625
I understood what that was later.

179
00:09:37,625 --> 00:09:40,708
It was funny at the time that there was a potato

180
00:09:40,708 --> 00:09:42,389
in the guy's monitor, though.

181
00:09:42,389 --> 00:09:45,071
So don't be the person who puts a potato in a monitor,

182
00:09:45,071 --> 00:09:45,592
is my point.

183
00:09:47,107 --> 00:09:50,729
This one is the more common one that you hear.

184
00:09:50,729 --> 00:09:53,512
Offering an opinion when unqualified.

185
00:09:53,512 --> 00:09:54,873
Look, here's the thing.

186
00:09:54,873 --> 00:09:57,995
If you're in a team, if you're in a bigger team especially,

187
00:09:57,995 --> 00:10:01,318
and that team has hired designers

188
00:10:01,318 --> 00:10:04,681
to come into design roles on your team,

189
00:10:04,681 --> 00:10:08,704
please don't usurp the authority and responsibility

190
00:10:08,704 --> 00:10:10,465
of those designers on your teams

191
00:10:10,465 --> 00:10:12,367
by constantly offering design opinions.

192
00:10:12,367 --> 00:10:14,048
I love that you have design opinions,

193
00:10:14,048 --> 00:10:15,369
if you have them and you're offering them.

194
00:10:15,938 --> 00:10:21,443
just make sure that you're helping the team use their time most wisely

195
00:10:21,443 --> 00:10:24,286
and boosting the cred of the people around you

196
00:10:24,286 --> 00:10:32,352
by giving them the responsibility of having and pushing forward those opinions.

197
00:10:32,352 --> 00:10:35,715
I actually, every year, I have at least one moment

198
00:10:35,715 --> 00:10:38,718
where I have to coach a new producer on this one.

199
00:10:40,972 --> 00:10:45,537
and then not asking other so this is goes hand in hand obviously with not

200
00:10:45,537 --> 00:10:49,262
you know kind of not speaking up or not feeling empowered but not not asking

201
00:10:49,262 --> 00:10:52,565
others for their opinion not asking enough questions not being curious

202
00:10:52,565 --> 00:10:54,768
enough what I'm looking for.

203
00:10:55,385 --> 00:10:58,767
really, especially with newer producers or people who are really curious.

204
00:10:58,767 --> 00:11:06,053
It becomes very helpful when you are uncovering the unknowns in your designs

205
00:11:06,053 --> 00:11:10,016
to have curious people around you, especially producers who are responsible

206
00:11:10,016 --> 00:11:14,039
for understanding the scope of work that is being proposed.

207
00:11:14,380 --> 00:11:16,901
And so when you don't ask a lot of questions,

208
00:11:16,901 --> 00:11:19,623
and people for their opinions about the validity of things,

209
00:11:19,623 --> 00:11:22,485
the goodness of things, how deep problems are

210
00:11:22,485 --> 00:11:25,687
going to be in things, then you're not helping your team

211
00:11:25,687 --> 00:11:26,788
as much as you could.

212
00:11:26,788 --> 00:11:27,128
Self-control.

213
00:11:27,128 --> 00:11:36,875
Once in a while, and this goes for all team members,

214
00:11:36,875 --> 00:11:41,038
but it really hurts me when I see it

215
00:11:41,038 --> 00:11:42,659
from someone who's in production.

216
00:11:44,799 --> 00:11:47,824
your team's looking to you to be a leader,

217
00:11:47,824 --> 00:11:53,312
to be someone who sets the tone for adult behavior

218
00:11:53,312 --> 00:11:55,875
and professionalism in the team, usually.

219
00:11:55,875 --> 00:11:59,180
We want that of all members of our teams.

220
00:12:00,757 --> 00:12:03,119
you know, my discipline now is in production,

221
00:12:03,119 --> 00:12:05,060
so I can't control, per se,

222
00:12:05,060 --> 00:12:07,162
or give that same message to all other disciplines.

223
00:12:07,162 --> 00:12:09,024
I'll say, if you're in production,

224
00:12:09,024 --> 00:12:12,687
I'm hoping that you are consciously

225
00:12:12,687 --> 00:12:14,589
practicing self-control.

226
00:12:14,589 --> 00:12:15,750
There's a lot of ways to do that.

227
00:12:15,750 --> 00:12:17,972
We're not going to go into kind of all methods

228
00:12:17,972 --> 00:12:20,034
for all things here.

229
00:12:20,034 --> 00:12:21,655
I will ask you that you practice this.

230
00:12:23,783 --> 00:12:29,407
is an obvious one. However, a lot of times we see information being disseminated through

231
00:12:29,407 --> 00:12:34,109
electronic means that needs to be given face to face. Any time you coach somebody, I hope

232
00:12:34,109 --> 00:12:38,052
that is face to face. Never coach anybody over email or on a phone call.

233
00:12:38,492 --> 00:12:43,919
It can wait, unless it's disastrous, it can wait until you're face-to-face.

234
00:12:43,919 --> 00:12:47,283
Also, great news is best delivered face-to-face.

235
00:12:47,283 --> 00:12:52,871
It's way more impactful and you can also use it as a moment to coach in a positive direction,

236
00:12:52,871 --> 00:12:54,373
not just away from a negative direction.

237
00:12:59,043 --> 00:13:02,024
There's kind of damned if you do, damned if you don't things.

238
00:13:02,024 --> 00:13:05,586
There are a lot of these gotchas.

239
00:13:05,586 --> 00:13:08,247
So rather than say it's a failure

240
00:13:08,247 --> 00:13:11,768
to make a decision before you have all the information.

241
00:13:11,768 --> 00:13:13,209
I could have said that.

242
00:13:13,209 --> 00:13:16,370
But instead what I'll say is that the failure is not

243
00:13:16,370 --> 00:13:18,611
recognizing what the best alternative is.

244
00:13:18,611 --> 00:13:21,192
You have to make decisions within complete information.

245
00:13:21,192 --> 00:13:21,833
It's part of your job.

246
00:13:21,833 --> 00:13:24,754
You're going to try to uncover all the information you can.

247
00:13:25,115 --> 00:13:28,202
But really, you're going to have to make a lot of decisions

248
00:13:28,202 --> 00:13:29,425
with incomplete information.

