where all the important stuff that has to get sorted out

495
00:27:14,270 --> 00:27:18,034
between producers happens at these roundtables.

496
00:27:18,034 --> 00:27:21,398
No executive managers, no executive producers

497
00:27:21,398 --> 00:27:23,581
go to these meetings, that's by design.

498
00:27:24,580 --> 00:27:28,824
And I've had requests from other executives, hey, can I go to these meetings, hear more

499
00:27:28,824 --> 00:27:29,645
about what's happening?

500
00:27:29,645 --> 00:27:33,929
Well, no, because if you do that, they're not going to have the discussion they need

501
00:27:33,929 --> 00:27:34,389
between them.

502
00:27:34,389 --> 00:27:40,955
So what I want is I want that healthy peer community to be established in a studio, especially

503
00:27:40,955 --> 00:27:42,196
at our size and bigger.

504
00:27:42,196 --> 00:27:46,800
I mean, we're small compared to maybe what if any of you are from, say, Ubisoft Montreal

505
00:27:46,800 --> 00:27:48,642
or any of the larger studios.

506
00:27:48,642 --> 00:27:49,122
But even so.

507
00:27:50,043 --> 00:27:53,826
there has to be a healthy community of practice amongst producers.

508
00:27:53,826 --> 00:27:56,068
You can't do that when everybody's just working in their silo.

509
00:27:56,068 --> 00:28:06,337
On Borderlands 2, Sean Reardon, who's the senior producer on the project and I sat down

510
00:28:06,337 --> 00:28:12,302
and we were trying to figure out, because there were some things happening around the schedule,

511
00:28:12,302 --> 00:28:13,843
as always happens on any project.

512
00:28:14,264 --> 00:28:15,925
What's the formula?

513
00:28:15,925 --> 00:28:19,487
Actually, we started this discussion way back early in Borderlands 1 even.

514
00:28:19,487 --> 00:28:21,869
What's the formula for quality?

515
00:28:21,869 --> 00:28:27,392
What we care about is quality, and we're a meritocracy, and we need to create a compelling

516
00:28:27,392 --> 00:28:30,494
argument about why we need to get more time for something.

517
00:28:30,494 --> 00:28:31,515
How do we do that?

518
00:28:31,515 --> 00:28:36,558
Well, quality results from focus and time.

519
00:28:36,558 --> 00:28:40,501
We need to use these words and then turn them into something actionable as a studio for

520
00:28:40,501 --> 00:28:41,661
how we organize ourselves.

521
00:28:44,245 --> 00:28:47,708
Quick thing I'll say there is anything that distracts from

522
00:28:47,708 --> 00:28:49,669
focus is negative.

523
00:28:49,669 --> 00:28:52,932
So if you have people who are spending a lot of time

524
00:28:52,932 --> 00:28:56,174
streaming, if you're doing that, if taking a lot of smoke

525
00:28:56,174 --> 00:28:59,657
breaks, whatever, while that might not feel like a big deal

526
00:28:59,657 --> 00:29:03,399
on a day-to-day basis, you're creating a lot of debt over

527
00:29:03,399 --> 00:29:05,321
time that has to be paid.

528
00:29:05,321 --> 00:29:08,003
And that's something that you have to reinforce with a

529
00:29:08,003 --> 00:29:09,864
message with your team all the time.

530
00:29:09,864 --> 00:29:12,586
You can only do that, first of all, if you are setting a good

531
00:29:12,586 --> 00:29:12,907
example.

532
00:29:17,276 --> 00:29:20,840
Giving a heads up, so the military has this term Werno,

533
00:29:20,840 --> 00:29:22,022
a warning order.

534
00:29:22,022 --> 00:29:24,024
It's, hey, I'm about to tell you something's going to

535
00:29:24,024 --> 00:29:25,906
happen, here's the thing I'm going to tell you, and then

536
00:29:25,906 --> 00:29:27,168
the actual order comes later.

537
00:29:27,168 --> 00:29:29,991
And you have to remind people all the time that.

538
00:29:30,863 --> 00:29:33,444
there was a discussion about something that might require

539
00:29:33,444 --> 00:29:36,725
them to do work, they have to be prepared to do that work.

540
00:29:36,725 --> 00:29:39,585
Because if you don't do that, you have situations where,

541
00:29:39,585 --> 00:29:42,326
especially with leads who are really busy, they, I don't

542
00:29:42,326 --> 00:29:44,446
remember that ever being discussed, or I don't remember

543
00:29:44,446 --> 00:29:46,506
that being a thing I had to prepare work for, and I didn't

544
00:29:46,506 --> 00:29:49,767
create that job posting, and I didn't do the spec for that

545
00:29:49,767 --> 00:29:51,147
thing that had to happen.

546
00:29:51,147 --> 00:29:55,488
So you have to keep this cadence of information so that

547
00:29:55,488 --> 00:29:57,048
people remember there's a thing that they're

548
00:29:57,048 --> 00:29:58,028
going to have to do.

549
00:29:58,208 --> 00:29:59,509
By the way, I want to remind you,

550
00:29:59,509 --> 00:30:01,591
I want you to give this talk, or a version of it,

551
00:30:01,591 --> 00:30:04,132
for yourselves when you get home.

552
00:30:04,132 --> 00:30:11,537
And so think about what examples you can use for these.

553
00:30:11,537 --> 00:30:15,059
It's strange, but I think this happens

554
00:30:15,059 --> 00:30:15,819
in a culture where.

555
00:30:16,676 --> 00:30:20,217
performance reviews don't happen regularly,

556
00:30:20,217 --> 00:30:22,317
that we forget part of our job is

557
00:30:22,317 --> 00:30:24,657
to supervise what's happening.

558
00:30:24,657 --> 00:30:26,778
We're not just information handlers.

559
00:30:26,778 --> 00:30:29,278
We actually are responsible for the quality and result

560
00:30:29,278 --> 00:30:31,119
of the product that we're working on.

561
00:30:31,119 --> 00:30:34,719
And so supervision for a junior, and this

562
00:30:34,719 --> 00:30:37,320
is more geared towards junior producers,

563
00:30:37,320 --> 00:30:41,020
while I don't want you to act like you're the boss,

564
00:30:41,020 --> 00:30:43,401
I do want you to remember that you have a responsibility here.

565
00:30:43,401 --> 00:30:43,461
So.

566
00:30:45,374 --> 00:30:47,275
It's an easy one, just don't be negligent.

567
00:30:47,275 --> 00:30:51,097
Well, what happens next when we start to abdicate our

568
00:30:51,097 --> 00:30:55,899
authority in the role that we do have is we might do things

569
00:30:55,899 --> 00:30:58,020
like a very bad job at expectation management.

570
00:30:58,020 --> 00:31:00,722
Now, this ranges across all kinds of things.

571
00:31:00,722 --> 00:31:03,803
And unfortunately, it can become part of our culture if

572
00:31:03,803 --> 00:31:06,645
we're not careful, just the topic of poor expectation

573
00:31:06,645 --> 00:31:07,465
management.

574
00:31:07,465 --> 00:31:10,487
We see it in things like press tours, where we might say

575
00:31:10,487 --> 00:31:11,968
things about products that.

576
00:31:12,548 --> 00:31:15,629
We're correct at one time and then later didn't, we're not so correct.

577
00:31:15,629 --> 00:31:20,251
Or it might become something about what a role is, what we expect of people in their

578
00:31:20,251 --> 00:31:21,872
roles.

579
00:31:21,872 --> 00:31:26,434
It can be something about what the focus of our project is at the time, whether it's time

580
00:31:26,434 --> 00:31:26,834
or quality.

581
00:31:26,834 --> 00:31:29,015
You have to manage your triangle, right?

582
00:31:29,015 --> 00:31:33,476
And the triangle of time, quality.

583
00:31:34,695 --> 00:31:39,377
and money as something that you're responsible for managing,

584
00:31:39,377 --> 00:31:41,478
you have to know which of those is,

585
00:31:41,478 --> 00:31:44,440
there's always something that's a priority, okay?

586
00:31:44,440 --> 00:31:46,561
You can't have everything be the highest priority.

587
00:31:46,561 --> 00:31:50,022
And expectation management is knowing what the priorities are

588
00:31:50,022 --> 00:31:51,323
and clearly communicating those.

589
00:31:51,323 --> 00:31:52,823
And that can be caused,

590
00:31:52,823 --> 00:31:55,404
one of the things is having unchecked assumptions.

591
00:31:55,404 --> 00:32:00,747
And I had to counsel somebody about six months ago,

592
00:32:00,747 --> 00:32:02,988
kind of hand in hand with things getting through the cracks.

593
00:32:03,926 --> 00:32:08,127
not doing a very good job of actually checking information.

594
00:32:08,127 --> 00:32:11,668
So we know that in a communication model,

595
00:32:11,668 --> 00:32:14,429
there's the signal that's transmitted.

596
00:32:14,429 --> 00:32:17,169
Well, if you want to know if communications really happen,

597
00:32:17,169 --> 00:32:19,930
I did a talk on this last year, so let me touch on it here.

598
00:32:19,930 --> 00:32:21,810
You want to make sure that communication was actually

599
00:32:21,810 --> 00:32:23,551
received in the way that you intended it.

600
00:32:23,551 --> 00:32:25,851
And that is your responsibility.

601
00:32:25,851 --> 00:32:27,252
And it's funny to me how often.

602
00:32:29,053 --> 00:32:32,715
where it's easy for us to transmit communication.

603
00:32:32,715 --> 00:32:35,657
We're so willing to transmit communication,

604
00:32:35,657 --> 00:32:37,538
but we do a terrible job at making sure

605
00:32:37,538 --> 00:32:40,160
that that communication actually happened

606
00:32:40,160 --> 00:32:42,041
and that the signal went through

607
00:32:42,041 --> 00:32:44,762
and that the message was heard and is being acted on

608
00:32:44,762 --> 00:32:45,383
in the way that we intended.

609
00:32:45,383 --> 00:32:46,463
So I'm saying it's hard, it's not easy.

610
00:32:54,100 --> 00:32:55,861
Don't distribute your attention too much.

611
00:32:55,861 --> 00:32:59,042
It's easy for us to make too many commitments once.

612
00:32:59,042 --> 00:33:00,243
You can go too far, right?

613
00:33:00,243 --> 00:33:02,404
You can say, I'm going to enable the team to do everything.

614
00:33:02,404 --> 00:33:05,045
And then it's very, very quickly, easily,

615
00:33:05,045 --> 00:33:06,426
something we can fall into as a trap.

616
00:33:09,284 --> 00:33:12,706
We're getting close to wrapping up the failure part of this.

617
00:33:12,706 --> 00:33:16,249
So failure to deal with the producer's dilemma.

618
00:33:16,249 --> 00:33:18,350
This happens all the time.

619
00:33:18,350 --> 00:33:21,793
When you have somebody in a seat and you think, man, if I

620
00:33:21,793 --> 00:33:24,594
coach that person, I only have that one person who can do

621
00:33:24,594 --> 00:33:26,556
that thing, whatever it is.

622
00:33:26,556 --> 00:33:28,997
This might be my cert or platform specialist.

623
00:33:28,997 --> 00:33:32,220
Or hell, it could be the lead designer of the project.

624
00:33:32,220 --> 00:33:33,040
Could be anybody.

625
00:33:34,201 --> 00:33:41,863
When we fall into the trap of having to keep that one person, it could be that one bad seed that spoils the water, that poisons it for everybody.

626
00:33:41,863 --> 00:33:47,405
Poisoning the well, I see less of it these days in the industry, but it sure as hell still happens.

627
00:33:47,405 --> 00:33:54,047
I see a lot more qualified people, and we have grown a lot, which is good, but we still fall into this dilemma.

628
00:33:54,047 --> 00:33:58,168
And as a producer, you have to be kind of at the front lines of dealing with it.

629
00:34:04,154 --> 00:34:10,279
Candor and conflict in the industry, you're not everybody's buddy, right?

630
00:34:10,279 --> 00:34:12,180
You're not here to make friends with everyone.

631
00:34:12,180 --> 00:34:15,603
And your team needs to know that you're going to be straightforward with them.

632
00:34:15,603 --> 00:34:21,027
Because the second that they start feeling that you're full of shit, you've lost your

633
00:34:21,027 --> 00:34:22,368
credibility and your trust.

634
00:34:22,368 --> 00:34:26,271
And they know you're no longer able to be candid with them.

635
00:34:26,271 --> 00:34:28,933
They'll feel that you're trying to politic with them.

636
00:34:28,933 --> 00:34:33,657
When you move from candor to politics, you've lost the team.

637
00:34:34,582 --> 00:34:39,405
And you need to know when that might happen and avoid that danger.

638
00:34:39,405 --> 00:34:46,609
I've worked in environments where there's a lot of politics happening, especially when

639
00:34:46,609 --> 00:34:46,849
I was.

640
00:34:47,408 --> 00:34:50,712
working with the military or back when I was working in music,

641
00:34:50,712 --> 00:34:53,034
there's a lot of politics happening all the time

642
00:34:53,034 --> 00:34:59,982
because there are scarcity in jobs or scarcity in attention.

643
00:34:59,982 --> 00:35:03,947
And once you get yourself into a role

644
00:35:03,947 --> 00:35:07,651
where you can make sure there's a lot of attention you can give to members of your team,

645
00:35:08,071 --> 00:35:10,273
or a lot of jobs that you can provide,

646
00:35:10,273 --> 00:35:12,955
or coaching moments that you can have with them,

647
00:35:12,955 --> 00:35:15,657
you know, you can do away with some of the politics.

648
00:35:15,657 --> 00:35:17,599
But you have to be direct with people,

649
00:35:17,599 --> 00:35:19,460
or else they'll feel that you're full of shit,

650
00:35:19,460 --> 00:35:20,441
and they can't trust you.

651
00:35:20,441 --> 00:35:22,162
And then it's much harder for you to do your job,

652
00:35:22,162 --> 00:35:23,583
and you probably won't be in your job very long.

653
00:35:23,583 --> 00:35:24,604
So this is kind of the complement to that.

654
00:35:31,215 --> 00:35:36,019
That will happen, it can happen if you're not comfortable with being direct with people.

655
00:35:36,019 --> 00:35:40,283
If you have fear, it's okay to be afraid, but you have to practice being candid.

656
00:35:40,283 --> 00:35:43,065
A lot of people have to practice that.

657
00:35:43,065 --> 00:35:45,867
It's not something that's natural to everyone.

658
00:35:45,867 --> 00:35:49,511
So hopefully you're in an environment where you can practice that, but you have to find

659
00:35:49,511 --> 00:35:50,531
opportunities to practice.

660
00:35:50,531 --> 00:35:50,792
Don't ever lie.

661
00:35:55,144 --> 00:35:58,746
So moving from there, that's sort of a crawl walk phase.

662
00:35:58,746 --> 00:36:03,968
I'm going to talk about the things that I think make for

663
00:36:03,968 --> 00:36:04,808
super producers.

664
00:36:04,808 --> 00:36:07,129
Again, not quite at the business EP level.

665
00:36:07,129 --> 00:36:08,450
There's a little bit of that.

666
00:36:08,450 --> 00:36:14,232
But between myself and the senior producers I work with

667
00:36:14,232 --> 00:36:16,393
at Gearbox, and some at the publishers we work with,

668
00:36:16,393 --> 00:36:21,035
here's a few qualities that I'd like to see you all

669
00:36:21,035 --> 00:36:23,156
practice and think about intentionally.

670
00:36:23,956 --> 00:36:27,938
So here's the first one.

671
00:36:27,938 --> 00:36:29,779
You have to be the person now.

672
00:36:29,779 --> 00:36:33,721
Say you're moving from junior producer or mid-level producer

673
00:36:33,721 --> 00:36:34,442
into senior producer.

674
00:36:34,442 --> 00:36:37,543
You're the person responsible for the project for the team,

675
00:36:37,543 --> 00:36:41,786
or you're enabled by your lead to be one of those people.

676
00:36:41,786 --> 00:36:43,227
Bad things have to stop.

677
00:36:44,095 --> 00:36:46,016
And you have to go through a practice.

678
00:36:46,016 --> 00:36:48,858
You should go through a process on a milestone basis,

679
00:36:48,858 --> 00:36:51,399
some regular basis, where you are evaluating.

680
00:36:51,399 --> 00:36:54,141
You might do this as a mid-mortem, a post-mortem,

681
00:36:54,141 --> 00:36:56,942
simply something that you do as an activity with your team

682
00:36:56,942 --> 00:36:58,403
members, your leads.

683
00:36:58,403 --> 00:37:01,284
You have to be constantly identifying things.

684
00:37:01,865 --> 00:37:05,025
Those that need to continue, those that need to stop,

685
00:37:05,025 --> 00:37:06,946
new things that you should start doing,

686
00:37:06,946 --> 00:37:08,366
things that need to be discussed.

687
00:37:08,366 --> 00:37:11,387
Okay, you are gonna come across things that have to stop.

688
00:37:11,387 --> 00:37:16,108
And the only way to break a cycle in a bad culture

689
00:37:16,108 --> 00:37:19,448
or to avoid some pitfall for quality of project,

690
00:37:19,448 --> 00:37:22,309
things that make studios go out of business,

691
00:37:22,309 --> 00:37:25,510
is to make bad stuff stop as quickly as possible.

692
00:37:25,510 --> 00:37:27,870
And it is your responsibility to do that.

693
00:37:32,117 --> 00:37:33,738
The best producers walk around.

694
00:37:33,738 --> 00:37:35,939
I talked about not sending all your messages

695
00:37:35,939 --> 00:37:37,539
through electronic means.

696
00:37:37,539 --> 00:37:40,500
If you have a team, if it's not just a fully distributed team,

697
00:37:40,500 --> 00:37:43,081
I'm saying in the realm of the feasible,

698
00:37:43,081 --> 00:37:44,121
you should be walking around.

699
00:37:44,121 --> 00:37:45,982
Your face should be everywhere.

700
00:37:45,982 --> 00:37:47,502
People should know who you are.

701
00:37:47,502 --> 00:37:49,123
You should know who your dev team members are.

702
00:37:49,123 --> 00:37:51,904
You should know as much as you possibly can about them.

703
00:37:51,904 --> 00:37:55,585
And there are some really tangible reasons for that

704
00:37:55,585 --> 00:37:59,427
and some popular thinking about the walking manager.

705
00:38:01,218 --> 00:38:07,240
One of those is the ability to send that message and rally people around your causes.

706
00:38:07,240 --> 00:38:14,361
You have to be able to use words and convey your words in a way about what your goals are

707
00:38:14,361 --> 00:38:20,543
that gets your team members excited and impelled to do what's needed for your project.

708
00:38:20,543 --> 00:38:25,164
So you have to be the person. You might think it's corny or you didn't come from a background

709
00:38:25,164 --> 00:38:26,745
where this is a thing that you did or you're...

710
00:38:27,245 --> 00:38:30,606
introverted or whatever, you have to practice helping rally people.

711
00:38:30,606 --> 00:38:35,808
Maybe you're not the right one to actually be the rally point and do the hoo-ah moment.

712
00:38:35,808 --> 00:38:37,068
That's fine.

713
00:38:37,068 --> 00:38:37,848
That's fine.

714
00:38:37,848 --> 00:38:45,431
But you need to be part of the solution to get people excited and using their passions.

715
00:38:45,431 --> 00:38:51,253
The best producers show and practice.

716
00:38:51,847 --> 00:38:56,471
The things they want in the macro, they do it in the micro

717
00:38:56,471 --> 00:39:01,215
all the time, every day, in the smallest ways, because it

718
00:39:01,215 --> 00:39:04,778
sends a vibe across your entire team and your studio

719
00:39:04,778 --> 00:39:09,022
about what your expectations are from the smallest to the

720
00:39:09,022 --> 00:39:11,865
largest, it's common themes.

721
00:39:11,865 --> 00:39:16,489
So here are some in that, basically according to that

722
00:39:16,489 --> 00:39:16,869
triangle.

723
00:39:17,868 --> 00:39:20,210
The team's food, again, details.

724
00:39:20,210 --> 00:39:25,036
Clearly communicating every time you branch or have a build.

725
00:39:25,036 --> 00:39:27,439
Don't let those get by you.

726
00:39:27,439 --> 00:39:30,582
People need to be aware of the state of the product.

727
00:39:31,850 --> 00:39:35,653
that loop from intent to QA, depending on how you manage

728
00:39:35,653 --> 00:39:39,717
QA and quality in your studio, this could be a huge thing.

729
00:39:39,717 --> 00:39:42,920
Not just because you want to reduce bugs and defects, but

730
00:39:42,920 --> 00:39:48,165
because your QA team typically is your front line of getting

731
00:39:48,165 --> 00:39:52,950
a broad view of the quality of the state of the next piece of

732
00:39:52,950 --> 00:39:54,852
software that you're releasing.

733
00:39:57,385 --> 00:39:59,526
So this cadence of useful communication, the best

734
00:39:59,526 --> 00:40:01,807
producers maintain that cadence and are

735
00:40:01,807 --> 00:40:02,907
intentional about it.

736
00:40:02,907 --> 00:40:05,588
You don't just, when you have information, send it.

737
00:40:05,588 --> 00:40:09,630
You think about regularly what is the kind of digest?

738
00:40:09,630 --> 00:40:13,072
What are the kinds of information that you can

739
00:40:13,072 --> 00:40:16,553
provide on a regular basis so that you set an expectation

