00:40:16,553 --> 00:40:18,494
with your team that you are going to

741
00:40:18,494 --> 00:40:19,555
provide them information?

742
00:40:20,075 --> 00:40:22,196
Even if you don't have a lot to say,

743
00:40:22,196 --> 00:40:24,137
provide a little bit on a regular basis

744
00:40:24,137 --> 00:40:25,958
so they know that information's happening

745
00:40:25,958 --> 00:40:26,879
and they'll feel a lot more secure

746
00:40:26,879 --> 00:40:27,939
about decisions being made

747
00:40:27,939 --> 00:40:28,559
that they're not aware of.

748
00:40:28,559 --> 00:40:30,501
The best producers have a strong moral compass.

749
00:40:30,501 --> 00:40:31,781
I don't think I need to say a lot about that.

750
00:40:43,116 --> 00:40:47,138
But maybe it's not obvious to people coming in the industry.

751
00:40:47,138 --> 00:40:48,978
It was interesting to me, this came up a lot

752
00:40:48,978 --> 00:40:51,659
when I was talking with my production friends

753
00:40:51,659 --> 00:40:53,680
about what makes for great producers,

754
00:40:53,680 --> 00:40:55,821
is that your team can rely on you

755
00:40:55,821 --> 00:40:58,662
to make decisions for the right reasons.

756
00:40:58,662 --> 00:41:02,864
And that your team can recover even

757
00:41:02,864 --> 00:41:06,805
if consequences of decisions are negative.

758
00:41:06,805 --> 00:41:10,567
You have to practice what you want.

759
00:41:12,330 --> 00:41:15,192
You have to have a shipping mentality all the time.

760
00:41:15,192 --> 00:41:18,014
And now, again, the industry is really big now.

761
00:41:18,014 --> 00:41:22,617
So we have people in many areas of development where maybe you

762
00:41:22,617 --> 00:41:24,839
don't ship things in the same way that I do,

763
00:41:24,839 --> 00:41:25,819
cross-platform and PC.

764
00:41:25,819 --> 00:41:28,921
Maybe you're, hell, maybe you're shipping every day if

765
00:41:28,921 --> 00:41:30,443
you're in mobile.

766
00:41:30,943 --> 00:41:33,224
So there you definitely have to keep that shipping mentality.

767
00:41:33,224 --> 00:41:34,765
But you also might be doing things

768
00:41:34,765 --> 00:41:39,047
where efficacy is much higher than,

769
00:41:39,047 --> 00:41:41,308
or you might think efficacy for, say,

770
00:41:41,308 --> 00:41:43,509
if you're doing an educational game or something,

771
00:41:43,509 --> 00:41:45,350
is higher than pure entertainment value.

772
00:41:45,350 --> 00:41:48,111
And so your mentality is more around efficacy.

773
00:41:48,111 --> 00:41:50,292
That's fine, but we're making games still.

774
00:41:50,292 --> 00:41:51,333
So we want to make fun things that

775
00:41:51,333 --> 00:41:52,353
are going to get out there.

776
00:41:52,353 --> 00:41:53,494
When you don't include the team.

777
00:41:58,561 --> 00:42:00,243
in decisions about the thing they're making,

778
00:42:00,243 --> 00:42:04,047
then they're not bought in, and then they're out.

779
00:42:04,047 --> 00:42:06,850
A lot of people see it as binary.

780
00:42:06,850 --> 00:42:08,832
A lot of developers, they're passionate,

781
00:42:08,832 --> 00:42:10,674
and they're going to see it as a binary decision.

782
00:42:10,674 --> 00:42:12,255
They're either in or they're out.

783
00:42:12,255 --> 00:42:13,016
You've got to keep them in.

784
00:42:13,016 --> 00:42:15,018
And the way you keep them in is by keeping them engaged.

785
00:42:17,508 --> 00:42:19,209
Best producers are playing games.

786
00:42:19,209 --> 00:42:21,050
Hopefully you're playing games with your teams.

787
00:42:21,050 --> 00:42:24,311
It's a great team building exercise if you're playing

788
00:42:24,311 --> 00:42:25,651
cooperative games.

789
00:42:25,651 --> 00:42:28,112
Competitive's cool too, but if you're playing co-op games

790
00:42:28,112 --> 00:42:31,393
with hard missions, then those are great team building

791
00:42:31,393 --> 00:42:33,414
moments, also shows you're a gamer, you're buying those

792
00:42:33,414 --> 00:42:34,194
cred points.

793
00:42:34,194 --> 00:42:36,495
So producer, a lot of people who are not in production.

794
00:42:43,430 --> 00:42:46,793
A lot of us who are in production think of the producer as a scheduler.

795
00:42:46,793 --> 00:42:48,494
I think of the scheduler as the project manager.

796
00:42:48,494 --> 00:42:52,736
I think of project management as part of what producers do.

797
00:42:52,736 --> 00:42:57,039
We've created titles for people who spend more time in scheduling than in other areas

798
00:42:57,039 --> 00:42:58,040
of production.

799
00:42:58,040 --> 00:43:03,723
But if you want to be a great producer, you better be awesome at scheduling.

800
00:43:03,723 --> 00:43:09,327
You can go other directions in production that aren't as scheduling focused.

801
00:43:11,013 --> 00:43:14,376
When somebody in finance, say, asks you,

802
00:43:14,376 --> 00:43:16,358
are you going to hit this milestone?

803
00:43:16,358 --> 00:43:21,542
And you, I wouldn't say lie, but you make a reach statement

804
00:43:21,542 --> 00:43:23,244
and say yes without actually knowing

805
00:43:23,244 --> 00:43:25,926
what the state of the project as compared to your schedule is,

806
00:43:25,926 --> 00:43:29,550
then you're putting yourself in a dangerous situation.

807
00:43:30,370 --> 00:43:37,072
What I prefer is people to come from a background of having to work with creative departments

808
00:43:37,072 --> 00:43:43,553
and building lists, going very deep into those lists, maintaining data to do trend analysis

809
00:43:43,553 --> 00:43:49,435
with what the outcome of the work from those lists was over time, so that you really quickly

810
00:43:49,435 --> 00:43:57,116
build your – well, quickly – so that you build your bullshit filter and have the encompassing

811
00:43:58,693 --> 00:44:01,676
how quickly people can get things done on your team,

812
00:44:01,676 --> 00:44:06,039
what the kinds of appropriate work is for your team to commit to, etc.

813
00:44:06,039 --> 00:44:09,542
The hard thing there, I think,

814
00:44:09,542 --> 00:44:11,984
because I still don't see it often enough

815
00:44:11,984 --> 00:44:16,608
with even just people who are only focused on scheduling and project management,

816
00:44:16,608 --> 00:44:17,549
is in bracketing.

817
00:44:17,549 --> 00:44:24,015
If you have any responsibility for scheduling at all,

818
00:44:24,959 --> 00:44:27,928
And even if you don't, and you just

819
00:44:27,928 --> 00:44:30,035
want to make sure you know what the hell's going on

820
00:44:30,035 --> 00:44:30,677
in your project.

821
00:44:31,945 --> 00:44:38,289
I hope that you can regularly have conversations about and build your own backwards plans and

822
00:44:38,289 --> 00:44:39,450
forwards plans.

823
00:44:39,450 --> 00:44:45,394
Compare the two and then bracket the window of when you think things are going to land.

824
00:44:45,394 --> 00:44:50,537
Use that as part of doing your backlog building if you're doing Agile.

825
00:44:50,537 --> 00:44:56,401
Use it as part of your milestone commitments or even your initial full project schedules.

826
00:44:57,318 --> 00:45:02,463
The more you do that over the time, the better you're actually going to get at knowing how

827
00:45:02,463 --> 00:45:06,267
much scope you should be committing to with the kinds of people you have, as opposed to

828
00:45:06,267 --> 00:45:09,870
guessing or just guessing.

829
00:45:09,870 --> 00:45:11,572
And ask a lot of questions for those things.

830
00:45:18,223 --> 00:45:21,304
Going back to, say, music, that's definitely talent

831
00:45:21,304 --> 00:45:25,366
management, A&R, artisan repertoire, kind of like

832
00:45:25,366 --> 00:45:29,068
building bands or groups or working with them to make sure

833
00:45:29,068 --> 00:45:30,768
that they're being promoted or doing the best

834
00:45:30,768 --> 00:45:31,629
kind of work they can.

835
00:45:31,629 --> 00:45:33,450
It's the same thing in games.

836
00:45:33,890 --> 00:45:38,071
It is a talent management business, and hopefully you know that.

837
00:45:38,071 --> 00:45:43,853
It's not just getting random people in and building a schedule around them, but rather

838
00:45:43,853 --> 00:45:49,815
over time, especially in a studio environment, really crafting what the team is like and

839
00:45:49,815 --> 00:45:53,316
who's responsible for what things, so your composition is good.

840
00:45:53,316 --> 00:45:58,438
Senior people tend to want to mentor others, or at least rely on the experience they have

841
00:45:58,438 --> 00:45:59,958
and know that it's being listened to.

842
00:45:59,958 --> 00:46:02,339
So you want to have the right mix of senior and junior people.

843
00:46:05,455 --> 00:46:09,638
You only go to war with the army that you have, right?

844
00:46:09,638 --> 00:46:11,099
So make sure on behalf of your team

845
00:46:11,099 --> 00:46:12,960
that you're committing to the things that they can do.

846
00:46:12,960 --> 00:46:16,503
You need to know what their growth plans are also,

847
00:46:16,503 --> 00:46:18,024
so you know what kinds of challenges

848
00:46:18,024 --> 00:46:18,904
they want to accomplish next.

849
00:46:18,904 --> 00:46:22,647
You have to constantly be talking

850
00:46:22,647 --> 00:46:27,110
about what the goals were and whether or not

851
00:46:27,110 --> 00:46:29,912
you hit them and celebrating those successes when

852
00:46:29,912 --> 00:46:32,334
they happen, but always providing, kind of bread

853
00:46:32,334 --> 00:46:33,875
crumbing the goals for your teams.

854
00:46:35,770 --> 00:46:38,131
If you don't know what the growth plans are for your team

855
00:46:38,131 --> 00:46:40,633
members, please go find out or build them

856
00:46:40,633 --> 00:46:42,454
if you haven't already.

857
00:46:42,454 --> 00:46:45,956
You have to get inside the heads of your team members

858
00:46:45,956 --> 00:46:47,857
so that you know what's possible,

859
00:46:47,857 --> 00:46:49,798
not just what you've already committed to,

860
00:46:49,798 --> 00:46:52,240
but what's possible with the team that you have

861
00:46:52,240 --> 00:46:55,081
and where your gaps might be for what's next.

862
00:46:55,081 --> 00:46:56,222
So I think all of us are only going

863
00:46:56,222 --> 00:47:00,265
to stay in this industry if we're able to innovate,

864
00:47:00,265 --> 00:47:01,665
if we're able to

865
00:47:02,787 --> 00:47:06,776
capitalize on the teams that we've built or are going to build in the future.

866
00:47:06,776 --> 00:47:09,964
We can't do that if we don't go deeper into knowing the motivations of our people.

867
00:47:15,001 --> 00:47:16,942
Your decision-making framework's really important.

868
00:47:16,942 --> 00:47:19,442
It's also very important that you be able to communicate it.

869
00:47:19,442 --> 00:47:22,884
And that's really hard for many producers

870
00:47:22,884 --> 00:47:25,284
to communicate that they even have a decision-making

871
00:47:25,284 --> 00:47:25,584
framework.

872
00:47:25,584 --> 00:47:28,706
It's easy to say you're making decisions based on common sense.

873
00:47:28,706 --> 00:47:31,506
It's really hard to say you're making decisions

874
00:47:31,506 --> 00:47:34,107
based on any particular framework or approach.

875
00:47:34,107 --> 00:47:37,568
I mention a few things here, and I'm

876
00:47:37,568 --> 00:47:39,509
going to ask if you're not familiar with these,

